<subSubSection lastPageId="22" lastPageNumber="605" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="21.[811,1453,1603,1851]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[813,923,1603,1627]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">Remarks.</emphasis>
In the key to 
<taxonomicName authorityName=", Macquart" authorityYear="1827" box="[1060,1195,1603,1627]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1060,1195,1603,1627]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">Elaphropeza</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
of 
<collectingCountry box="[1229,1336,1603,1627]" name="Singapore" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">Singapore</collectingCountry>
(
<bibRefCitation author="Grootaert P &amp; Shamshev I" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" pagination="1 - 162" refId="ref17047" refString="Grootaert P &amp; Shamshev I (2012) The fast-running flies (Diptera, Hybotidae, Tachydromiinae) of Singapore and adjacent regions. European Journal of Taxonomy, 5: 1 - 162." type="journal article" year="2012">Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2012</bibRefCitation>
) 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2015" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2015" box="[1035,1141,1635,1659]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[1035,1141,1635,1659]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">E. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1155,1284,1635,1659]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
runs to couplet 67. These are species with scutellum entirely yellow. 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert" authorityYear="2007" box="[813,1062,1699,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asiophila">
<emphasis box="[813,1062,1699,1723]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">Elaphropeza asiophila</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
and 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2015" box="[1122,1258,1699,1723]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Stilpon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ubinensis">
<emphasis box="[1122,1258,1699,1723]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">E. ubinensis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
have a darkened haltere and acrostichals extending to the base of the scutellum. 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2015" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2015" box="[811,1033,1763,1787]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[811,1033,1763,1787]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">Elaphropeza pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1051,1182,1763,1787]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
has yellow halteres and the acrostichals also extending to the base of the scutellum so we let it run to couplet 70.
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[813,1452,1889,2084]" box="[813,1450,1889,1911]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">67. Scutellum entirely yellow ....................................................68</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[813,1452,1889,2084]" box="[813,1450,1918,1940]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">– Scutellum largely brown or black .......................................74</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[813,1452,1889,2084]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">68. Haltere darkened. Acrostichal bristles extending to base of scutellum. Postpedicel at least 4.5 times as long as wide..69</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="21.[813,1452,1889,2084]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">
– Haltere yellow. Acrostichal bristles lacking on prescutellar depression (except 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2015" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2015" box="[1062,1166,2033,2055]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida" status="new species">
<emphasis box="[1062,1166,2033,2055]" italics="true" pageId="21" pageNumber="604">E. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, 
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[1183,1313,2033,2055]" pageId="21" pageNumber="604" rank="species">new species</taxonomicNameLabel>
). Postpedicel shorter...................................................................................70
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,776,189,730]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">
69. Postpedicel about 6.0 times longer than wide. Metanotum reddish-yellow (
<collectingCountry box="[340,440,218,240]" name="Singapore" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">Singapore</collectingCountry>
)...................................................... 
<emphasis box="[184,358,248,269]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">.............................</emphasis>
<taxonomicName authority="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 2007" authorityName="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert" authorityYear="2007" box="[361,773,247,269]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="asiophila">
<emphasis box="[361,479,247,269]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">E. asiophila</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Shamshev IV &amp; Grootaert P" box="[487,773,247,269]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605" pagination="1 - 164" refId="ref17350" refString="Shamshev IV &amp; Grootaert P (2007) Revision of the genus Elaphropeza Macquart (Diptera: Hybotidae) from the Oriental Region, with a special attention to the fauna of Singapore. Zootaxa, 1488, 1 - 164." type="journal article" year="2007">Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 2007</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,776,189,730]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">
– Postpedicel about 4.5 times longer than wide. Metanotum brownish (
<collectingCountry box="[285,385,304,326]" name="Singapore" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">Singapore</collectingCountry>
)............................................................... ............................. 
<taxonomicName authority="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 2007" authorityName="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert" authorityYear="2007" box="[360,773,333,355]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Stilpon" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="ubinensis">
<emphasis box="[360,479,333,355]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">E. ubinensis</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Shamshev IV &amp; Grootaert P" box="[487,773,333,355]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605" pagination="1 - 164" refId="ref17350" refString="Shamshev IV &amp; Grootaert P (2007) Revision of the genus Elaphropeza Macquart (Diptera: Hybotidae) from the Oriental Region, with a special attention to the fauna of Singapore. Zootaxa, 1488, 1 - 164." type="journal article" year="2007">Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 2007</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,776,189,730]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">
70. Fore tibia and tarsus, mid and hind tarsomere 5 brownish. Abdominal tergites 4 and 5 with squamiform setae. Male: cerci broadly fused, digitiform; right epandrial lamella truncate apically, lacking spines ............................................................ ................................... 
<taxonomicName authority="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 2007" authorityName="Shamshev &amp; Grootaert" authorityYear="2007" box="[400,773,477,499]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="furca">
<emphasis box="[400,479,477,499]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">E. furca</emphasis>
<bibRefCitation author="Shamshev IV &amp; Grootaert P" box="[487,773,477,499]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605" pagination="1 - 164" refId="ref17350" refString="Shamshev IV &amp; Grootaert P (2007) Revision of the genus Elaphropeza Macquart (Diptera: Hybotidae) from the Oriental Region, with a special attention to the fauna of Singapore. Zootaxa, 1488, 1 - 164." type="journal article" year="2007">Shamshev &amp; Grootaert, 2007</bibRefCitation>
</taxonomicName>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,776,189,730]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">– Legs with only tarsomere 5 brown. Different combination of characters............................................................................ 71a</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,776,189,730]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">
71a. Abdominal tergites 4 and 5 with squamiform setae. Scutum almost uniformly covered with short setae (sparser on prescutellar depression) (
<collectingCountry box="[426,526,621,643]" name="Singapore" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">Singapore</collectingCountry>
) ......... 
<taxonomicName authority="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev, 2015" authorityName="Grootaert &amp; Shamshev" authorityYear="2015" box="[592,688,621,643]" class="Insecta" family="Hybotidae" genus="Elaphropeza" kingdom="Animalia" order="Diptera" pageId="22" pageNumber="605" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="pallida" status="sp. nov.">
<emphasis box="[592,688,621,643]" italics="true" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">E. pallida</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
<taxonomicNameLabel box="[696,774,622,643]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605" rank="species">sp. nov.</taxonomicNameLabel>
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="22.[136,776,189,730]" pageId="22" pageNumber="605">– Abdominal tergite 4 at most with slightly flattened setae, tergite 5 with squamiform setae. Acrostichals 2–4-serial, lacking on prescutellar depression.......................................................71b</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
